parameters:
"No way, I can't believe the enhanced Tina-chan got
defeated..."

"Phew, well, it's fine. If I can just escape now, with the
hidden budget I can ask Belra to..."

"Oh? You know about the hidden budget and even Belra's
location? That's very interesting... I'd really like you to
share that with us."
"Selphie was looking at the lab's layout, you know?"

"There was an unnatural spot, so we figured you might try to
escape from here, and I've been on the lookout."

"Too bad, huh? You were planning to activate the anti-
tracking trap and escape from Selphie and the others,
weren't you?"

"Thanks to you being so engrossed in Selphie and Tina's
fight, I had time to disarm the traps up to here."

"Well, I just smashed through them really... It's soundproof
here, you didn't hear it, did you?"

"We're done here, right? I want to meet up with Tina and the
others quickly too."

"For now, I'll just beat you until you can't move... for
now."
"I've been waiting for you without being told, you know!!"
And so, this rescue operation came to a close.

Afterward, following Maroges' testimony, they headed to
Belra's location where she awaited them without any attempt
to flee.

"Oh? Is that you, Suelle-kun? Did you really rescue
everyone?"

"Impressive, who would have thought you'd be the winner of
the game."

"Hehe, you're quite a good man, aren't you? Since you've
come all the way to my house, how about it, I don't mind
sharing my bed with you tonight?"
"You knew we were coming and yet you didn't try to escape."

"I don't know if you've set up a trap, but whatever you do
is futile. My companions have surrounded the place. If you
resist..."

"Resist? I wouldn't dream of it. This is a game, and since
you've won, I'll follow the rules."

Suelle felt a sense of discomfort from the word 'rules' that
Bellra had mentioned several times.

"...Could it be that you didn't escape not because you
didn't want to, but because you couldn't?"

Bellra showed a slightly surprised expression at Suelle's
words.
"Oh? How did you figure that out?"
"It's not conclusive evidence. Just a hunch."
"The purpose is merely play... I believe that's true."

"But still, for Bellra, who has used all sorts of cowardly
tactics, to adhere to the rules and not escape, it just
doesn't sit right with me."

Suelle couldn't believe that the Bellra in front of him
would protect the game's rules to the point of putting
herself in jeopardy.
"From there... I just thought maybe you couldn't escape."

"Hmm... Well, it's fine. You would have realized it on your
own eventually, so I'll tell you as a special treat."

"Ancient spellcraft is a technique for creating rules, you
see?"

"Yes, creating a miniature garden called 'rules.' That's
what ancient spellcraft is."

"But that doesn't mean you can create any rule you want.
There has to be balance, you know?"

"Especially since the stronger the shackles are on oneself,
the stronger the rules that can be created for the opponent.
The more I take on these rules as shackles, the more
effective they become."

"Yes, the power of my garden is the game. The conditions of
the game become the very shackles that bind me."

That means, if Bellra sets conditions for the opponent or
has pre-established game rules, she herself must adhere to
them.
"But how can you have such power..."

"Of course. If what you're saying is true, it's different
from the spellcasting we use, which ends after its effect is
applied on the spot."

The terrifying thing is the power of the rules that continue
without a supply of energy. Even if the structure of the
spellcraft is different, Suelle thought that there must be a
source of power supply necessary.

"Hehe, haven't you realized it? Even if the structure of
ancient spellcraft is different, the original power is the
same. Do you understand why?"

"Then this will be quick. To conclude, what you call modern
spellcraft is actually a world-scale rule created by ancient
spellcraft."

"Does that mean... all current spellcraft functions under
the rules of ancient spellcraft?"

"Yes, originally there was no such thing as spellcraft in
this world. It was just that the world was altered to create
and make usable the rule called spellcraft."

That's the true nature of what you call spellcraft, Bellra
added.

"Doesn't that also mean this? If one could completely
understand ancient spellcraft, they could twist the rules of
this world."

If Bellra's story is true, then the power involved in
contracts of servitude is almost semi-permanent.

After all, it would be bound within the framework of natural
phenomena of the world.

"Do you understand now? In my case, I am bound by the rule
of the game, but within the game, I can exert an absolute
power that corresponds to it."

"However, conversely, due to the condition of my contract
with Suelle-kun—if I help his companions, I will surrender
quietly—I cannot escape."
Indeed, what Bellra is saying is likely true.
However, Suelle felt a snag in the story just now.

"I understand. But you haven't told the whole truth either,
have you?"

"Contracts of servitude should become void if they are
terminated midway, right?"

"The reason you didn't escape. It wasn't that you couldn't
escape, but rather you didn't want to break the rules and
risk destroying the garden you created, right?"

"If the garden of rules collapses, all the contracts of
servitude affecting this country would be nullified. I
believe you deliberately followed the rules and allowed
yourself to be captured to avoid that."

"I heard it from the three of them; Rise and Selphie made
contracts directly with you, Bellra."

"But Tina made a contract with Maroges. Maroges, who can't
use ancient spellcraft."

"Could it be that contracts of servitude are contagious
within the rules?"

Contagious. In other words, someone who has been placed
under a contract of servitude can impose another contract of
servitude on a different person.

"Maroges and Gugukas, along with the other men, have such
personalities. Even if you can use ancient spellcraft,
there's no guarantee of your safety."

"There's only one way to create a situation where they
absolutely won't retaliate... if they're under a contract of
servitude."

If the source of ancient spellcraft's power is the world's
rules, then once activated, the contract of servitude could
be made by anyone affected by those rules, even without
Bellra being present, Suelle thought.

Because as long as it's within the rules, there's no need
for the person themselves to cast the spell. Anyone who has
entered the game board and joined Bellra's side could
potentially do it.

If that's the case, it also explains how Bellra was able to
infiltrate the nation's core so quickly. The contracts of
servitude spread from person to person.

"Suelle-kun. Just as you said, I have spread the roots of
servitude contracts throughout this country."

That means there's no need to destroy the miniature garden
and flee because this country has already been taken over by
the rules.

It's easier and safer to issue commands to those under a
contract of servitude and escape.
"But why did you tell me all this?"

If Bellra hadn't mentioned it, I wouldn't have noticed. If
she hadn't said anything, I could have easily escaped this
predicament.

The reason she taught Suelle this, despite the fact that
once caught, it wouldn't be considered a violation of
Suelle's rules. The benefit she discarded to tell Suelle.

"It's like I'm giving a lecture on ancient spellcraft, isn't
it?"
At Bellra's words, Suelle's body jolted.
"There's a saying that curiosity killed the cat."

"But you know? Even if you understand that, you can't stop.
Especially people like you."

"You will continue to study ancient spellcraft and reach its
deepest secrets."

"For our, no, our shared ambition to unravel ancient
spellcraft and take control of the world."

"No, you are already one of us. Your talent will surely
awaken ancient spellcraft and you will definitely be seduced
by its charm and power."

"Especially someone like you, surrounded by strong
companions and lamenting your own lack of power."

At those words, this time he couldn't find anything to say
in return.

"Fufufu, perhaps we've talked too long. I'm looking forward
to that time."

As if his role was over, Bellra was captured without any
resistance.

Bellra's last words. Suelle still doesn't know as much about
ancient spellcraft as Bellra does.

But if I could obtain a power that could overturn the world,
could I remain true to myself without being drowned by that
power?

It's precisely because Suelle has tasted his own
powerlessness many times that Bellra's words seep into him
like they're entwining around him.

Even though he knows it's a sweet trap set by Bellra to
pique his interest.

Afterward, Suelle touched the bodies of people from the
nation's core and the justice department, regardless of
their gender.

Of course, it was to undo the enslavement contract and
brainwashing that Bellra had mentioned.

Currently, only those who can be trusted not to be
brainwashed are left in charge of Bellra's detention.
Even then, Bellra did not resist or set any traps.

To Suelle, it seemed as if Bellra was entrusting the future
to someone superior to himself.

At any rate, with this, Bellra should be unable to do
anything for a while, and Suelle felt a momentary relief
before an unexpected situation arose.

To start with the conclusion, Suelle is training his body
for that battle.

However, it's not combat he's training for. He's working on
his physical endurance, not his strength.
For the purpose of running away? Some might think so.

But that's not it either; Suelle's opponent is not someone
he can simply escape from.

So why is he training? I think you'll understand if you see
the daily battles Suelle faces.
